\
THREADS\
\
- a thread is akin to a worker\
- is an instance of java.lang.Thread\
\
\
Thread States\
- New				-	an instance has been created\
- Runnable			-	about to run\
- Running				-	is running\
- Blocked				-	can only be reached from a thread in running state, only progresses to runnable state\
- Waiting				-	from this state a thread can only go to blocked state\
- Time Waiting			-	e.g. invoked by sleep();\
- Dead/Terminated\
\
\
Thread scheduler moves thread from runnable state to running state and vice versa\
\
- Threads have a priority of 5 by default\
\
\
\
THREAD METHODS\
\
sleep()		-		puts the thread to sleep, is a blocking method\
wait()		-		makes the thread release the lock on an object, is a blocking method\
\
\
\
\
TASK\
\
- is akin to a work that needs to be done\
- is an instance of java.lang.Runnable\
\
\
thread.start() - causes a call stack to be created for the thread and run() method of the task is pushed onto the stack\
\
\
Try to think of a thread in terms of the pieces of code that need to run\
\
\
NOTE: Class Thread implements runnable. So you can extend Thread in your own class and implement a running task.\
But good OOD is to keep the task(runnable) class/object separate to the Thread class/object.\
\
\
\
